---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "Scalp Health Explained: Why Hair Care Often Fails Before It Starts";
const description =
  "Most hair problems don’t start in the hair itself. This guide explains scalp health, common misconceptions about ingredients, and why balance—not extremes—matters for long-term scalp comfort.";

const ogTitle = title;
const ogDescription =
  "Hair issues often begin at the scalp. Learn how scalp biology works, why “chemical-free” is the wrong lens, and how balanced care supports long-term scalp health.";
const ogType = "article";
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  ogTitle={ogTitle}
  ogDescription={ogDescription}
  ogType={ogType}
>
  <article class="content content-education">
    <h1>Scalp Health: The Part of Hair Care Most People Overlook</h1>

    <section>
      <p>
        Hair care usually starts with the hair you can see — strands, length,
        shine, volume. But most persistent hair problems don’t start in the hair
        itself. They start at the scalp.
      </p>

      <p>
        Issues like hair fall, flakes, itching, excessive oiliness, dryness, or
        sensitivity are often treated with stronger products or frequent changes
        in routine. In many cases, this approach manages symptoms rather than the
        underlying cause.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Hair Problems Rarely Start in the Hair</h2>

      <p>
        When hair begins to thin, break, or shed excessively, the instinct is to
        treat the strands. But once hair leaves the scalp, it is biologically
        inactive.
      </p>

      <p>
        Most common hair concerns are linked to what happens before hair emerges:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Disrupted scalp barrier</li>
        <li>Imbalanced oil production</li>
        <li>Irritation or inflammation</li>
        <li>Poor cleansing habits</li>
        <li>Overuse or misuse of products</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What the Scalp Actually Is</h2>

      <p>
        The scalp is a complex biological environment. It includes protective
        skin layers, hair follicles, oil glands, and a natural microbial system
        that helps maintain balance.
      </p>

      <p>
        Compared to facial skin, the scalp contains more oil glands, experiences
        higher product buildup, and is often cleansed less intentionally.
      </p>
    </section>

