            <rect x="60" y="92" width="280" height="40" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
            <text x="200" y="112" text-anchor="middle" font-size="14">Hair follicles</text>

            <!-- Oil glands (support layer) -->
            <rect x="70" y="160" width="260" height="28" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/>
            <text x="200" y="174" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13">Oil glands</text>
        </svg>

        <figcaption>
            The scalp is made up of layered skin structures, with hair follicles playing
            a central role in overall scalp function.
        </figcaption>
        </figure>


    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Why “Chemical-Free” Is the Wrong Lens</h2>

      <p>
        The idea of chemical-free hair care is misleading. Everything applied to
        the scalp interacts through chemistry — including water.
      </p>

      <p>
        The real considerations are purpose, dose, safety, and stability.
        Preservatives, pH adjusters, and stabilizers exist to support product
        integrity and scalp compatibility.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Where Natural Ingredients Actually Help</h2>

      <p>
        Natural ingredients can support scalp comfort when used intentionally —
        often as emollients, carriers, or complementary components within a
        balanced formulation.
      </p>

      <p>
        Their effectiveness depends on processing, stability, and how they work
        alongside functional ingredients.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>A Simple Framework for Understanding Scalp Problems</h2>

      <ol>
        <li>Barrier disruption</li>
        <li>Microbial imbalance</li>
        <li>Inflammation and sensitivity</li>
        <li>Poor cleansing habits</li>
        <li>Product overuse or misuse</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        This framework explains why no single product works universally and why
        consistency matters more than extremes.
      </p>
    </section>

